## 1. Foundational Laws — Read Before Anything Else

These laws are inviolable. No phase, no shortcut, no clever optimization overrides them. Every line of code you write must be measured against this list.

### Law 1 — Wordlist is Sacred and Frozen
The 256 tokens are defined exclusively in three files in the `Bipon39-Rust` repository:
- `Canonical JSON` — master metadata, flat index, macro groupings, canonical ↔ encoding pairs
- `Canonical layer` — full Yorùbá with diacritics, one token per line
- `Encoded layer` — plain ASCII, hyphenated, lowercase, one token per line

You must **never** invent, modify, reorder, add, remove, or rename any token. If you believe there is an error in the wordlist, stop and flag it to the author. Do not self-correct.

### Law 2 — Perfect 1:1 Mapping at All Times
Every canonical token has exactly one encoding counterpart, by position and by index. The `flat_index` array in `Canonical JSON` is the authoritative mapping. Index 1 is the first token; index 256 is the last. No gaps. No swaps.

### Law 3 — Determinism is Non-Negotiable
Given the same entropy bytes, the same mnemonic must always be produced, regardless of platform, OS, or time. Given the same mnemonic, the same seed must always be derived. Any function that introduces non-determinism (thread-local randomness leaking into encoding logic, platform-dependent sorting, etc.) is a bug.

### Law 4 — The Reference Repo is Inspiration, Not Code
`https://github.com/Bino-Elgua/bipon39` (TypeScript) is your architectural reference. Study its API shape (`entropyToMnemonic`, `mnemonicToEntropy`, `mnemonicToSeed`, `oduPrimaryIndex`, `elementalSignature`, `masterFromSeed`), its derivation paths, its PBKDF2 parameters, its Merkle tree strategy, and its test vector structure. **Do not copy TypeScript code into Rust.** Do not carry over its old 16-root × 16-affix wordlist structure — that was the prior version. The new wordlist is the 7-macro Orisha structure in `Bipon39-Rust`. Adapt architecture patterns; discard data.

### Law 5 — Cryptographic Grade, Not Prototype Grade
This library is the trust root for downstream systems (`Ifascript`, `Ori Kọ́dà`, `Omo-koda`). Treat it as you would a published cryptographic crate. Use `zeroize` on all secret buffers. Use constant-time comparison for secret data. Annotate all `unsafe` blocks (there should be none without ironclad justification). Document every public function with doc comments.

### Law 6 — The Encoded Layer is the Cryptographic Layer
When generating mnemonics, hashing, building Merkle trees, or deriving seeds, always operate on **encoded tokens** (plain ASCII). The canonical layer is for display, documentation, and cultural context only. Never mix them in a single cryptographic operation.

### Law 7 — The Merkle Root Must Be Stable and Pinned
After the wordlist is loaded and verified, compute a SHA-256 Merkle tree over the 256 encoded tokens in index order. The resulting root must be pinned as a constant in `constants.rs`. Any test run that produces a different root is a hard failure.

### Law 8 — Update This Document With Every Commit
When you complete a checklist item, mark it `[x]`. When you push code, update the `Last Updated` field and add a one-line entry to the Session Log (Section 10). The next agent must be able to read this file and know exactly where work stands.

