```

**Agent instruction:** Parse this file at build time or embed the encoding layer statically. The `flat_index` array is your single source of truth for the ordered list. `index` field is 1-based. Internally, map to 0-based for array indexing (token at `flat_index[0]` has global index 1, bit value 0x00).

### 2.2 Canonical Layer
**Path:** `Canonical layer`
**URL:** `https://github.com/Bino-Elgua/Bipon39-Rust/blob/main/Canonical%20layer`

Plain text file, one token per line, 256 lines total, in index order. Used for display functions and verification. Do not use these strings for any hash, Merkle, or seed derivation operation.

### 2.3 Encoded Layer
**Path:** `Encoded layer`
**URL:** `https://github.com/Bino-Elgua/Bipon39-Rust/blob/main/Encoded%20layer`

Plain text file, one ASCII token per line, 256 lines total, in index order. This is the cryptographic wordlist. All mnemonic generation, parsing, Merkle computation, and PBKDF2 input use tokens from this layer only.

### 2.4 Validation at Load Time
When the library loads its wordlist (whether from embedded static data or from files at runtime), it must verify:
1. Exactly 256 encoded tokens are present.
2. No two encoded tokens are identical (uniqueness).
3. All encoded tokens match the regex `^[a-z][a-z0-9]*(-[a-z][a-z0-9]*)*$` (lowercase, hyphens only as separators, no leading/trailing hyphens).
4. Token count per macro matches the locked distribution: `[88, 20, 28, 28, 32, 32, 28]`.
5. The Merkle root computed from the encoded layer matches the pinned constant in `constants.rs`.

