## 11. Known Risks and Edge Cases

### 11.1 Merkle Root Recomputation Required
The TypeScript reference repo documents a pinned Merkle root of `0ab1fafa...`. This root was computed over the **old** 16-root × 16-affix wordlist structure. The new wordlist is entirely different. The correct Merkle root for the Orisha-macro 256-token encoded list must be freshly computed in Phase 1.D. Do not copy the TypeScript root value.

### 11.2 PBKDF2 Salt Unicode
The salt prefix `"BIPỌ̀N39 seed"` contains Unicode (Ọ̀, N with subscript dot, etc.). When converted to bytes for PBKDF2, use UTF-8 encoding. The TypeScript reference uses `Buffer.from(...)` which defaults to UTF-8. Rust's `.as_bytes()` on a `&str` is also UTF-8. Confirm alignment.

### 11.3 Passphrase NFKD Normalization
The TypeScript reference normalizes the passphrase to NFKD before concatenating to the salt. This ensures that visually identical passphrases with different Unicode representations produce the same seed. The `unicode-normalization` crate in Rust handles this. Do not skip this step.

### 11.4 Checksum Word Boundary in Odù Index
The TypeScript `oduPrimaryIndex` function must be studied carefully to determine whether the checksum word (last word in the mnemonic) is included in the XOR reduction. The choice must be documented and match the TypeScript behavior exactly for cross-implementation consistency.

### 11.5 Encoding ASCII and Hyphen Characters
All encoded tokens use only lowercase `[a-z]` and hyphens `-`. No digits appear in any token (verify against actual data during Phase 1 testing). The regex in Section 2.4 allows digits for future-proofing but should be narrowed to `[a-z]+(-[a-z]+)*` if the actual tokens are purely alphabetic.

### 11.6 Termux / Android Environment
The author runs all commands manually in Termux on Android. This means:
- No CI agent can push code on the author's behalf.
- All `cargo` commands (build, test, clippy, fmt, bench) are run by the author.
- Agents provide code and the author runs it. Agents do not execute shell commands.
- When writing instructions for the author, be explicit and command-by-command.

### 11.7 No Modification of Source Files in `data/`
The files in `data/` are copies of the authoritative wordlist files. They must never be edited by an agent or tool. If the author updates the wordlist (which would be an extraordinary event), they update the repo-root source files first and then recopy to `data/`. The agent then recomputes and repins the Merkle root.

